00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:02.340
So when building the
site, performance

00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:03.520
was really important.

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:05.480
We wanted to make sure
people were engaged,

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:08.760
that the site loads quickly,
the games are responsive.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:11.840
And the Chrome Developer Tools,
particularly the timeline view,

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:13.670
is really important for that.

00:09:13.670 --> 00:09:17.340
When we added snow, we saw an
immediate drop in frame rate,

00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:21.397
probably for about 50 frames
per second down to 10 or 15.

00:09:21.397 --> 00:09:22.980
And we used the
Chrome Developer Tools

00:09:22.980 --> 00:09:26.590
to figure exactly-- figure out
exactly what Chrome was doing.

00:09:26.590 --> 00:09:28.490
So it turned out
whenever a piece of snow

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:29.940
fell to the bottom
of the page, it

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:32.030
was triggering a whole
page re-layout, which

00:09:32.030 --> 00:09:33.260
is quite expensive.

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:34.880
And we had a lot of snow.

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:38.470
So the Chrome Developer Tools
were really useful there.

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:42.761
There were also really good for
testing your responsive layout,

00:09:42.761 --> 00:09:43.260
right.

00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:44.840
You can emulate mobile devices.

00:09:47.530 --> 00:09:50.010
And the Web Fundamentals website
is a really good resource

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:55.640
for both performance and
multi-device layouts.

00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:59.790
To keep the site responsive,
we used a module system.

00:09:59.790 --> 00:10:04.140
So each of those experiences we
crafted into a separate module

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:08.840
so that the site loaded really
quickly upon first load.

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:10.980
When the user goes
into a game, they

00:10:10.980 --> 00:10:12.920
load that module,
which preloads all

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:16.420
of its assets such
as images and audio

00:10:16.420 --> 00:10:19.624
and shows a loading bar
like this to the user, just

00:10:19.624 --> 00:10:21.040
to keep them
informed and engaged.

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:29.070
We made really heavy use of
Google Analytics as well,

00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:31.290
not just to figure out
where people were engaged

00:10:31.290 --> 00:10:32.831
and where we could
make improvements,

00:10:32.831 --> 00:10:34.750
but also to track all
of the errors that

00:10:34.750 --> 00:10:36.310
happened on the page.

00:10:36.310 --> 00:10:39.610
So by adding a global
error listener,

00:10:39.610 --> 00:10:42.540
we were able to send those
errors over to Google Analytics

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:45.900
to figure out any problems that
we were having in production.

00:10:45.900 --> 00:10:50.620
We actually found a bug that
was only manifesting in IE 10

00:10:50.620 --> 00:10:53.130
