So it was really important
that that game, and those sorts

00:13:05.690 --> 00:13:07.640
of experiences, stay responsive.

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:11.080
And we could only really get
that level of responsiveness

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:13.120
again through a native app.

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:15.060
The other advantage
of being a native app

00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:18.270
is that we implemented
notifications.

00:13:18.270 --> 00:13:20.810
In fact, just one notification,
and that notification

00:13:20.810 --> 00:13:25.530
went off when Santa took
off on Christmas Eve.

00:13:25.530 --> 00:13:28.370
And it was really fun, because
suddenly we started to see all

00:13:28.370 --> 00:13:31.250
of these people posting on
Google+ and Twitter that, hey,

00:13:31.250 --> 00:13:33.550
my phone just told
me Santa's taken off.

00:13:33.550 --> 00:13:35.050
And they would tap
that notification

00:13:35.050 --> 00:13:38.730
and jump straight into
that map experience.

00:13:38.730 --> 00:13:42.110
But one bit of feedback that
we had from our early testing

00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:45.060
was, make that
notification silent.

00:13:45.060 --> 00:13:48.480
And make sure it doesn't
vibrate the phone or tablet.

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:51.500
Because when Santa takes
off, around half the world

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:52.290
is asleep.

00:13:52.290 --> 00:13:54.519
So they didn't want to get
woken up at 3:00 AM just

00:13:54.519 --> 00:13:56.185
because Santa's flying
around the world.

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:02.320
One of my favorite
part of the app

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:06.070
was the ability to use the
Google Maps API for Android.

00:14:06.070 --> 00:14:09.190
And you know, that the best
thing for me for this API

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:10.840
is the use of the camera.

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:12.440
And so it's not
just a 2D camera.

00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:14.070
It's actually a 3D camera.

00:14:14.070 --> 00:14:16.590
So you'll see as Santa
arrives here at Sydney,

00:14:16.590 --> 00:14:20.180
the camera zooms in but
also tilts ever so slightly

00:14:20.180 --> 00:14:24.410
to give a really good
sort of perspective.

00:14:24.410 --> 00:14:27.340
And as you zoomed in on various
cities around the world,

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:30.420
where we had support for it,
3D buildings show up as well.

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:32.790
And they start
popping up on the map.

00:14:32.790 --> 00:14:36.300
It just gives a really
immersive experience.

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:40.290
Another part of adding
immersiveness to our map

00:14:40.290 --> 00:14:44.350
here was the way that we wanted
the camera to follow Santa.

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:47.060
We really wanted it to feel
like there was someone holding

00:14:47.060 --> 00:14:50.890
a camera from way up high,
kind of keeping track of Santa

00:14:50.890 --> 00:14:52.110
as he traveled.

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:55.190
And in order to do
so, we made sure

00:14:55.190 --> 00:14:58.090
that Santa wasn't always at
the center of the screen.

00:14:58.090 --> 00:14:59.840
So you'll often
see that the camera

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:01.670
rotates and spins around.

00:15:01.670 --> 00:15:04.900
And sometimes it actually
gets ahead of Santa

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:06.240
and waits for Santa to catch up.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:07.710
And sometimes it falls behind.

00:15:07.710 --> 00:15:09.310
And then it catches up.

00:15:09.310 --> 00:15:11.190
So we were able to put
these sorts of effects

00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:15.450
in to just make the experience
that much more immersive.

00:15:15.450 --> 00:15:17.550
We called this Santa Cam.

00:15:17.550 --> 00:15:19.090
Yes, I know-- very original.

00:15:22.110 --> 00:15:24.780
On Android, we wanted this app
to be available everywhere.

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:27.830
So again, like a web experience
where we were typically

00:15:27.830 --> 00:15:31.040
targeting Chrome,
Gingerbread devices

00:15:31.040 --> 00:15:33.750
would have been excluded from
using Chrome for Android.

00:15:33.750 --> 00:15:35.420
We wanted to make
sure that this app was

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:37.320
available to all of those users.

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:40.150
And we wanted to make sure it
was available across screen

00:15:40.150 --> 00:15:42.590
sizes and form factors.

00:15:42.590 --> 00:15:46.790
So we built a responsive
layout on our apps as well.

00:15:46.790 --> 00:15:50.300
Now, if you look at the middle
screen shot and the screen shot

00:15:50.300 --> 00:15:52.159
to the very right,
you'll see that we've

00:15:52.159 --> 00:15:54.450
got a difference between
portrait layouts and landscape

00:15:54.450 --> 00:15:55.560
layouts.

00:15:55.560 --> 00:15:57.720
We've vertically stuck
the portrait layout,

00:15:57.720 --> 00:16:01.880
whereas on landscape we've got
the two views side by side.

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:04.460
But we were also able to put
in this little summary mode

00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:07.180
that you can see on the phone on
the left, where you can get rid

00:16:07.180 --> 00:16:09.100
of the dashboard and
see more of the map

00:16:09.100 --> 00:16:11.416
and see Santa travel
around the world,

00:16:11.416 --> 00:16:13.290
and just have a little
summary at the bottom.

00:16:13.290 --> 00:16:16.100
And that summary was like
a carousel, where we still

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:18.870
wanted to show those various
statistics from the dashboard,

00:16:18.870 --> 00:16:21.010
but we just swiped
them along one by one.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:23.420
Wed' show how many
presents were delivered,

00:16:23.420 --> 00:16:25.860
or what his previous
destination was, or how long

00:16:25.860 --> 00:16:27.045
he had been in flight.

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:31.420
Games.

00:16:31.420 --> 00:16:34.060
This was really fun
building and testing.

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:36.320
So this game you see
here is the jetpack game

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:38.920
written by an engineer
on our team, Bruno.

00:16:38.920 --> 00:16:42.170
And it was actually built
using a custom OpenGL

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:44.650
engine that he wrote in Java.

00:16:44.650 --> 00:16:48.410
And yeah, this one was one
that we certainly played a lot

00:16:48.410 --> 00:16:51.791
when we were testing the game.

00:16:51.791 --> 00:16:54.794
For the other two games, if
you look at the tilt game

00:16:54.794 --> 00:16:56.460
at the bottom left,
and you can't really

00:16:56.460 --> 00:16:58.820
see the tilting here, but
in order to control it,

00:16:58.820 --> 00:17:00.820
it uses the
accelerometer, as well as

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:02.980
the memory match game
on the right hand side.

00:17:02.980 --> 00:17:05.930
They just use the standard
Android view hierarchy.

00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:08.640
Because we were able to,
again, build a very custom

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:11.300
look and feel and make
it feel like a true game

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:13.619
without having to go to
the extent of building up

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:17.680
a whole engine for it.

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:20.200
Again building using
the right tools

00:17:20.200 --> 00:17:24.280
for the job was-- for the type
of job you have, was paramount.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:26.400
We wanted the
jetpack race, again,

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:29.350
to be faster in fluid
whilst being responsive.

00:17:29.350 --> 00:17:31.720
And in fact, when Bruno
tested it on the Nexus One,

00:17:31.720 --> 00:17:34.500
he got something like
45 frames per second,

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:37.280
with something like 25
presents on screen at a time.

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:39.742
And so you can imagine
on a device that old

00:17:39.742 --> 00:17:41.950
when it performed that well,
from that point forward,

00:17:41.950 --> 00:17:47.104
everything was just fast
and fluid from there.

00:17:47.104 --> 00:17:50.270
But playing games is great.

00:17:50.270 --> 00:17:53.400
But what I like to do is I
like to play games with others.

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:55.920
And these games were
still single player games.

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:58.750
So we started integrating
Play Game services

00:17:58.750 --> 00:17:59.990
into Santa Tracker.

00:17:59.990 --> 00:18:03.010
What Play Game services allows
you to do is sign in with

00:18:03.010 --> 00:18:05.810
your Google+ account and then
participate in the leader

00:18:05.810 --> 00:18:08.410
boards and earn achievements.

00:18:08.410 --> 00:18:09.820
So from our point
of view, it was

00:18:09.820 --> 00:18:12.650
a way of driving
engagement in the app.

00:18:12.650 --> 00:18:16.700
But it took off in a way that
we hadn't really anticipated.

00:18:16.700 --> 00:18:19.660
For starters, people that
used the Santa Tracker

00:18:19.660 --> 00:18:22.280
app are much better
gamers than our team.

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:24.900
In the first 15 minutes
or so of the app being

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:30.630
live, our scores had been,
best scores, had been eclipsed.

00:18:30.630 --> 00:18:33.520
The important thing about the
integration with the Play Game

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:37.970
services here was how we
suggested users sign in.

00:18:37.970 --> 00:18:40.587
So what you see
with a lot of games

00:18:40.587 --> 00:18:42.420
these days is that as
soon as you launch it,

00:18:42.420 --> 00:18:45.150
it prompts you to say sign
in with your credentials.

00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:47.410
We didn't want to be
so aggressive about it.

00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:50.220
What we did instead is
that we waited for the user

00:18:50.220 --> 00:18:50.940
to play the game.

00:18:50.940 --> 00:18:52.900
And then on the score,
on the high score

00:18:52.900 --> 00:18:55.110
screen at the bottom,
you'll see we ask them,

00:18:55.110 --> 00:18:58.560
would you like to sign
in to unlock achievements

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:01.080
and participate
in leader boards.

00:19:01.080 --> 00:19:03.610
And our sign in rate was
actually very, very high.

00:19:03.610 --> 00:19:06.970
People really loved
being a part of this.

00:19:06.970 --> 00:19:11.300
So in the months leading up
to Santa Tracker's launch,

00:19:11.300 --> 00:19:14.820
Google announced a new
product, Chromecast.

00:19:14.820 --> 00:19:16.540
And immediately,
we were fans of it.

00:19:16.540 --> 00:19:19.560
We wanted to see Santa
on the big screen.

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:23.310
So Google Santa Tracker was
actually one of the early apps

00:19:23.310 --> 00:19:26.340
to integrate with Chromecast.

00:19:26.340 --> 00:19:30.800
integrating with Chromecast,
however brought new challenges.

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:33.910
One, it was a big, huge screen.

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:36.810
And it was meant to be
a lean back experience.

00:19:36.810 --> 00:19:39.620
So that meant we needed to
take all of the controls

00:19:39.620 --> 00:19:41.100
away from the user.

00:19:41.100 --> 00:19:43.800
So you might be able to--
is you might have controls

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:48.720
on your website or on your phone
to zoom and move Santa around.

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:50.190
But we wanted to take that away.

00:19:50.190 --> 00:19:53.310
Your phone or your tablet
effectively acts like a remote.

00:19:53.310 --> 00:19:55.680
So you would drive
it from the phone,

00:19:55.680 --> 00:19:58.620
but you wouldn't necessarily
have any interactive controls

00:19:58.620 --> 00:20:00.590
on screen.

00:20:00.590 --> 00:20:03.960
Chromecast by the way, the
intention of Chromecast

00:20:03.960 --> 00:20:06.100
is that you don't
mirror what you're

00:20:06.100 --> 00:20:07.800
seeing on your phone or tablet.

00:20:07.800 --> 00:20:09.870
What you do is you launch
an experience on there

00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:11.630
that's tailored for that screen.

00:20:11.630 --> 00:20:15.300
In fact, Chromecast, the
physical size of a Chromecast

00:20:15.300 --> 00:20:18.260
is about the size of
a USB flash drive.

00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:20.140
It's actually a
low power device.

00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:22.280
But it runs the Chrome browser.

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:28.682
So when you cast to the TV,
it actually ran the website.

00:20:28.682 --> 00:20:30.140
And some of those
performance tools

00:20:30.140 --> 00:20:32.020
that Chris mentioned
earlier really

00:20:32.020 --> 00:20:34.650
became important, because
it's a low powered device.

00:20:34.650 --> 00:20:37.620
So some of the differences
that you might have seen,

00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:42.110
lower snow densities, or fewer
concurrent audio streams.

00:20:42.110 --> 00:20:45.194
So we definitely tailored
the experience for it.

00:20:47.980 --> 00:20:52.270
So on December 24th, Santa
takes off regardless of

00:20:52.270 --> 00:20:53.690
whether we're ready.

00:20:53.690 --> 00:20:55.880
So it's a really interesting
engineering project.

00:20:55.880 --> 00:20:57.880
Because we can't slip up.

00:20:57.880 --> 00:20:59.890
So it's really
important to us that we

00:20:59.890 --> 00:21:03.790
make sure we deliver a fantastic
experience on that day,

00:21:03.790 --> 00:21:05.850
because there is no
way for us to really

00:21:05.850 --> 00:21:08.600
revise it from
that point forward.

00:21:08.600 --> 00:21:12.820
So let me show you some of
the techniques that we use.

00:21:12.820 --> 00:21:17.010
This is what the desk of a
typical Android Google Santa

00:21:17.010 --> 00:21:19.060
Tracker engineer looks like.

00:21:19.060 --> 00:21:20.920
Most of our colleagues
walk past our desk

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:22.780
and don't believe
that we're working.

00:21:22.780 --> 00:21:27.100
But this is the way we kind
of test Santa in flight.

00:21:27.100 --> 00:21:30.040
And you'll see here that
we don't have 3,000 Android

00:21:30.040 --> 00:21:31.800
devices, because
it doesn't actually

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:34.520
require that many to test
this kind of experience.

00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:36.270
You have a mix of form factors.

00:21:36.270 --> 00:21:37.300
So we have some tablets.

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:38.550
We have some phones.

00:21:38.550 --> 00:21:40.860
And we have a mix
of screen sizes.

00:21:40.860 --> 00:21:42.750
And within these
devices as well,

00:21:42.750 --> 00:21:45.030
we have a mix of
operating system versions,

00:21:45.030 --> 00:21:47.140
different versions of Android.

00:21:47.140 --> 00:21:48.910
And basically, we
were able to represent

00:21:48.910 --> 00:21:50.830
the majority of
Android devices just

00:21:50.830 --> 00:21:53.870
with a fairly small collection.

00:21:53.870 --> 00:21:55.840
Leading up to it,
however we also

00:21:55.840 --> 00:21:58.780
need to do full simulations
of Santa in flight.

00:21:58.780 --> 00:22:01.402
We call those dry runs.

00:22:01.402 --> 00:22:03.110
And this is where the
whole Santa Tracker

00:22:03.110 --> 00:22:04.580
team, regardless
of whether you're

00:22:04.580 --> 00:22:06.163
working on the mobile
Apple, or you're

00:22:06.163 --> 00:22:09.070
working on the web or the
back end, we all get together

00:22:09.070 --> 00:22:11.950
and we simulate Santa
journeying across the world.

00:22:11.950 --> 00:22:14.120
Now in that simulation,
we have to assume

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:15.630
where Santa's going to land.

00:22:15.630 --> 00:22:18.500
Because on the day, I mean we
find out just in time updates

00:22:18.500 --> 00:22:21.100
from Santa in terms of
his position, right.

00:22:21.100 --> 00:22:23.280
So we make something
up for the simulation.

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:25.390
And we go through the whole day.

00:22:25.390 --> 00:22:28.810
And all of us, we have phones,
and tablets, and laptops,

00:22:28.810 --> 00:22:31.380
and desktops sort
of simulating Santa.

00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:33.870
We want to make sure
that if you turned it on

00:22:33.870 --> 00:22:36.760
at the beginning of his
journey, 25 hours later

00:22:36.760 --> 00:22:39.720
when he finishes, you're
able to run that through.

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:41.860
And we don't run into
any performance problems

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:43.690
or stability problems.

00:22:43.690 --> 00:22:47.590
This photo here is actually of
the Google Sydney reception.

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:50.750
One of our engineers, Jan-Felix,
got a little bit carried away

00:22:50.750 --> 00:22:52.790
with the dry run
and took is Nexus 10

00:22:52.790 --> 00:22:55.640
and hooked it up to our big
screen in the reception.

00:22:55.640 --> 00:22:57.690
And we basically took
it over for the day.

00:22:57.690 --> 00:23:01.200
So on that 15th of December when
we had visitors in that office,

00:23:01.200 --> 00:23:02.720
they were very
confused as to why

00:23:02.720 --> 00:23:06.104
Santa was flying
across their screens.

00:23:06.104 --> 00:23:07.770
CHRIS BROADFOOT: Yeah,
so as Ankur said,

00:23:07.770 --> 00:23:09.811
we need to make sure that
all of the applications

00:23:09.811 --> 00:23:11.040
work functionally.

00:23:11.040 --> 00:23:14.220
We also need to make sure that
they can take all of the load.

00:23:14.220 --> 00:23:17.960
We see over 100,000 concurrent
users on the website

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:20.060
at some points in time.

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:23.950
And at other points in
time, over 50% of those

00:23:23.950 --> 00:23:26.160
were from mobile.

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:29.750
This is what the traffic
shape looks like.

00:23:29.750 --> 00:23:31.920
When I first joined
the team, I was

00:23:31.920 --> 00:23:34.230
told that we just get
a barrage of users.

00:23:34.230 --> 00:23:35.730
But that's actually
not quite true.

00:23:35.730 --> 00:23:39.230
It's, as you can see, it's
kind of a gradual growth

00:23:39.230 --> 00:23:40.170
which plateaus.

00:23:40.170 --> 00:23:42.810
And then they all fall
off as Santa touches

00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:45.560
down in the North Pole.

00:23:45.560 --> 00:23:49.300
So to make sure the back ends
work, all of our apps work,

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:51.290
we run load tests.

00:23:51.290 --> 00:23:52.850
You can see the App
Engine dashboard

00:23:52.850 --> 00:23:55.050
while we're running
one of our load tests.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:58.390
So we actually took this one up
to 10,000 queries per second.

00:23:58.390 --> 00:24:01.900
And by taking it up that
far, we were pretty confident

00:24:01.900 --> 00:24:05.320
that we were going to be able
to support the main event.

00:24:05.320 --> 00:24:07.120
You can see the average
of our instances

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:08.780
was to 250 queries for second.

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:14.010
But we saw some of
them far up to 800 QPS,

00:24:14.010 --> 00:24:14.950
which was very good.

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:18.330
And I think this is
largely due to the Go

00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:21.510
runtime on App Engine,
which is really, really high

00:24:21.510 --> 00:24:22.342
performance.

00:24:22.342 --> 00:24:24.300
You can see the memory
consumption is quite low

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:27.860
as well, which is really good.

00:24:27.860 --> 00:24:31.910
This is what a graph from one of
Google's front end service-- oh

00:24:31.910 --> 00:24:33.870
sorry, back end
service, looks like.

00:24:33.870 --> 00:24:36.920
So I think this is from our
Google Maps tile server.

00:24:36.920 --> 00:24:39.540
You can see on either
side of Christmas Day,

00:24:39.540 --> 00:24:41.490
the traffic is
relatively smooth.

00:24:41.490 --> 00:24:44.100
But during Christmas Day
while Santa is running,

00:24:44.100 --> 00:24:47.000
the traffic gets
really, really spiky.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.430
You'll also notice that
the volume of traffic

00:24:49.430 --> 00:24:51.350
isn't that much higher either.

00:24:51.350 --> 00:24:53.360
This is because
the whole of Google

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:55.260
experiences a
little bit of a dip,

00:24:55.260 --> 00:24:58.380
so Santa Tracker kind of fills
that gap, which is really good.

00:24:58.380 --> 00:25:01.890
Just keeping our
back ends in shape.

00:25:01.890 --> 00:25:04.300
So the spiking
nature of the traffic

00:25:04.300 --> 00:25:06.410
is primarily because
everyone is looking

00:25:06.410 --> 00:25:08.940
at the exact same thing
at the exact same time.

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:12.210
So everyone is hitting
the same kind of requests.

00:25:12.210 --> 00:25:14.800
And the largest
spikes I think are

00:25:14.800 --> 00:25:18.050
because when Santa's
traveling quicker,

00:25:18.050 --> 00:25:20.720
say for example, over
the ocean, or just

00:25:20.720 --> 00:25:23.200
quickly across a continent
or something like that,

00:25:23.200 --> 00:25:26.820
then people are requesting
many, many more tiles.

00:25:26.820 --> 00:25:30.315
So we try to smooth that spiky
traffic using a technique

00:25:30.315 --> 00:25:31.950
called jitter.

00:25:31.950 --> 00:25:35.460
So the top half of this slide
shows our internal flags,

00:25:35.460 --> 00:25:37.820
which we can change
during the event.

00:25:37.820 --> 00:25:43.410
And that lets us
delay people randomly.

00:25:43.410 --> 00:25:44.780
And we start with two minutes.

00:25:44.780 --> 00:25:47.890
So we try to smooth people
out over a two minute period.

00:25:47.890 --> 00:25:51.770
So if you opened your phone
and your desktop machine,

00:25:51.770 --> 00:25:55.110
you may not actually see Santa
in exactly the same position.

00:25:55.110 --> 00:25:56.660
But they'll be pretty close.

00:25:56.660 --> 00:26:00.430
We can also control how
often our clients re-request

00:26:00.430 --> 00:26:02.260
these flags.

00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:04.610
And we jitter those
as well, of course,

00:26:04.610 --> 00:26:08.060
just to make sure that the
traffic to our API server

00:26:08.060 --> 00:26:11.440
is also quite smooth.

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:14.620
So these flags are stored
in the App Engine data store

00:26:14.620 --> 00:26:17.140
and are cached using
Memcache, and also

00:26:17.140 --> 00:26:18.820
with the local instance cache.

00:26:18.820 --> 00:26:21.850
It doesn't really matter if
these flags are bit stale.

00:26:21.850 --> 00:26:26.200
So we can just cache
them in memory.

00:26:26.200 --> 00:26:28.820
And those flags come
down to the client

00:26:28.820 --> 00:26:31.970
when they're re-requesting these
flags periodically as well.

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:35.970
So you'll see the time
offset field there.

00:26:35.970 --> 00:26:39.290
And that should
be the same value

00:26:39.290 --> 00:26:41.600
throughout that
user's experience.

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:45.910
So once you're delayed,
you're delayed that amount.

00:26:45.910 --> 00:26:49.060
We also use this
endpoint to safeguard

00:26:49.060 --> 00:26:50.760
against unexpected events.

00:26:50.760 --> 00:26:53.320
We haven't actually
had to use these flags.

00:26:53.320 --> 00:26:55.770
But we're able to turn
off entire experiences.

00:26:55.770 --> 00:26:58.780
For example, we could shut down
the tracker map on the Android

00:26:58.780 --> 00:27:01.990
application, or switch
off the entire website

00:27:01.990 --> 00:27:03.220
using these flags.

00:27:03.220 --> 00:27:05.690
We can also disable
particular features,

00:27:05.690 --> 00:27:07.210
